## Philosophical and Scientific Perspectives

Philosophy and science offer distinct but complementary approaches to knowledge seeking. Philosophy is concerned with framing questions and exploring normative issues—what should be—through rational inquiry. In contrast, scientific inquiry focuses on empirical evidence and testable hypotheses about what is ([Quora, 2017](https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-difference-between-philosophical-inquiry-and-scientific-inquiry)).

The pursuit of scientific knowledge is motivated by the desire to understand the natural world and solve practical problems. Scientific research provides answers to societal questions, contributing to technological advancement and improved quality of life ([JanetPanic.com, 2018](https://janetpanic.com/why-do-we-seek-knowledge-science/)).

Philosophically, knowledge is considered power, a concept famously articulated by Sir Francis Bacon. Knowledge empowers individuals by providing control over their environment and circumstances, enabling informed decision-making and success ([JanetPanic.com, 2018](https://janetpanic.com/why-do-we-seek-knowledge-science/)).

